                <head>No. 19<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>On the morning of May 15, three other meetings were held between members of the
                    Secretary of State’s party and officials of the Government of Jordan. At 10
                    a.m., MacArthur, <persName corresp="#p_BHA1">Byroade</persName>, and <persName
                        corresp="#p_LAG1">Lynch</persName> called on the Minister of Finance,
                        <persName corresp="#p_SSA1">Suleiman</persName> Sukkar, for a discussion of
                    economic and political problems. At 10:05 <persName corresp="#p_SHE1"
                        >Stassen</persName>, Mattison, and <persName corresp="#p_WTR1"
                        >Welling</persName> met with the Minister of Economy and Reconstruction, H.
                    E. Anwar Khatib, his Under Secretary, and two other members of his office staff.
                    They discussed Jordan’s need for economic and technical aid, and left before
                    10:30 so that <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">Stassen</persName> could join
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF2">Dulles</persName> in a meeting with refugee
                    leaders. At 10:30 MacArthur, <persName corresp="#p_BHA1">Byroade</persName>, and
                        <persName corresp="#p_LAG1">Lynch</persName> met with the Minister of
                    Education, <persName corresp="#p_TTAB1">Ahmad Tuqan</persName>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_TTAB1">Tuqan</persName> had spent eight months as the senior
                    Jordanian representative on the Mixed Armistice Commision, and gave the
                    Americans his views on the Jordanian-Israeli border situation. <pb facs="0091"
                        n="51" xml:id="pg_51"/> Memoranda of these conversations are in the
                    Conference files, lot 59 D 95, CF 156.</p>
            </div>
